### Mocking Rules
	Mock only true external boundaries:
	•	HTTP clients
	•	DB repositories
	•	cache clients
	•	message brokers
	•	filesystem
	•	date/time when needed
	•	random/uuid generators when determinism matters
	- Do not over-mock internal helpers if testing through public module behavior is reasonable.
	- Prefer simple explicit mocks over complex shared magic.
	- Reset mocks between tests.

Preferred patterns:

``` ts
jest.mock('../repositories/userRepository');
const mockedRepo = jest.mocked(userRepository);
```

or
``` ts
const dependency = {
  sendEmail: jest.fn(),
};
```

### Assertions

	•	Assert the important outcome only.
	•	Avoid asserting every intermediate step unless it matters to behavior.
	•	For complex objects, use:
        •	toEqual for exact structure
        •	toMatchObject for partial shape
        •	expect.objectContaining(...) when only some fields matter
	•	For async errors use:

```ts
await expect(service.doWork()).rejects.toThrow('message');
```

### Async Testing

	•	Always use await for async code.
	•	Do not mix done callback style with async/await unless absolutely necessary.
	•	Ensure rejected promises are asserted explicitly.
	•	Mock async dependencies with mockResolvedValue / mockRejectedValue.

Example:
```ts
    mockedRepo.findById.mockResolvedValue(user);
    await expect(service.getUser('123')).resolves.toEqual(user);
```

### Time and Randomness
	•	Freeze or mock time when testing time-based behavior.
	•	Stub random values, UUIDs, and non-deterministic generators.
	•	Prefer predictable inputs over relying on real clock time.

Example:

```ts
    jest.useFakeTimers().setSystemTime(new Date('2025-01-01'));
```

### Test Data
	•	Keep test data minimal and relevant.
	•	Build only the fields needed for the scenario.
	•	Prefer small local factories/helpers when repetition appears.
	•	Avoid giant fixtures unless truly needed.

#### Preferred:

```ts
const makeUser = (overrides = {}) => ({
  id: 'u1',
  email: 'test@example.com',
  isActive: true,
  ...overrides,
});
```

### Edge Cases

Always think about:
	•	empty input
	•	null/undefined input when relevant
	•	invalid values
	•	boundary numbers
	•	duplicate data
	•	partial failures
	•	unexpected dependency errors
	•	already-processed / idempotent cases

### Error Testing
	•	Verify both:
        •	the error condition
        •	any important side effects that must not happen
	•	When testing failures, confirm external calls were or were not made as expected.

Example:
```ts
    await expect(service.createUser(input)).rejects.toThrow(ValidationError);
    expect(emailClient.send).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
```

### Interaction Testing

Use interaction assertions only when behavior depends on collaboration with dependencies.

Examples:
	•	repository called with normalized email
	•	queue publish called once
	•	retry service not invoked for non-retryable error

Avoid excessive assertions like checking every single call if the return value already proves the behavior.

### Jest Best Practices
	•	Use beforeEach for shared clean setup.
	•	Prefer local setup inside the test if it improves readability.
	•	Use jest.clearAllMocks() or jest.resetAllMocks() as appropriate.
	•	Use jest.spyOn when observing real object methods.
	•	Keep mocks strongly typed where possible.
	•	Avoid hidden global state across test files.

### Preferred File Layout
	•	Keep unit tests in a mirrored __tests__ structure.
	•	Name tests consistently:
        •	fileName.test.ts
        •	fileName.spec.ts

### Coverage Guidance
	•	Do not chase 100% coverage blindly.
	•	Aim to cover critical business logic and meaningful branches.
	•	A missing assertion is worse than missing coverage.
	•	High-value tests matter more than many shallow tests.

### Anti-Patterns to Avoid
	•	Testing private methods directly
	•	Testing implementation details instead of public behavior
	•	Overusing snapshots for backend logic
	•	Huge brittle fixtures
	•	Real network/database in unit tests
	•	Copy-paste test cases with unclear differences
	•	Assertions with no behavioral value
	•	Multiple unrelated behaviors in one test
	•	Random sleeps/timeouts in tests

## When Writing New Tests

### For each function/module:
	1.	Identify the public behavior.
	2.	Cover the happy path.
	3.	Cover key edge cases.
	4.	Cover failure cases.
	5.	Mock external boundaries only.
	6.	Keep the test small and readable.

## Expected Style from the Assistant

### When generating Jest tests for this project:
	•	Use TypeScript-friendly Jest style where applicable.
	•	Follow Arrange / Act / Assert.
	•	Prefer explicit, readable mocks.
	•	Cover happy path, edge cases, and error path.
	•	Avoid integration-style tests unless explicitly requested.
	•	Avoid unnecessary comments except where structure improves clarity.
	•	Produce test code that is ready to paste into the codebase.

Example Template
```ts
describe('UserService.createUser', () => {
  const userRepository = {
    findByEmail: jest.fn(),
    create: jest.fn(),
  };

  const emailService = {
    sendWelcomeEmail: jest.fn(),
  };

  let service: UserService;

  beforeEach(() => {
    jest.clearAllMocks();
    service = new UserService(userRepository, emailService);
  });

  it('creates a user and sends a welcome email when email is new', async () => {
    // Arrange
    userRepository.findByEmail.mockResolvedValue(null);
    userRepository.create.mockResolvedValue({ id: 'u1', email: 'a@b.com' });

    // Act
    const result = await service.createUser({ email: 'a@b.com' });

    // Assert
    expect(userRepository.create).toHaveBeenCalledWith({ email: 'a@b.com' });
    expect(emailService.sendWelcomeEmail).toHaveBeenCalledWith('a@b.com');
    expect(result).toEqual({ id: 'u1', email: 'a@b.com' });
  });

  it('throws when email already exists', async () => {
    // Arrange
    userRepository.findByEmail.mockResolvedValue({ id: 'existing-user' });

    // Act + Assert
    await expect(service.createUser({ email: 'a@b.com' })).rejects.toThrow(
      'User already exists'
    );

    expect(userRepository.create).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
    expect(emailService.sendWelcomeEmail).not.toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
});
```